[{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"EditURL = \"../../../literate/tutorials/gettingstarted.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"Autoencoder                  Team:Shaolong, Ramnath Rao Bekal, Rahul Bhaskaram                                                       31/8/2024","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"1.Definition 1.Learning rate Too high a learning rate might cause the model to oscillate or even diverge during training, leading to poor convergence. This could result in poor quality of the graphics generated by the autoencoder, with significant loss of detail. Too low a learning rate might lead to excessively slow training and the model might get stuck in local minima. This could cause the autoencoder to generate overly smooth images that miss some important features.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"Epoch Number","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"Too few epochs might prevent the model from adequately learning the features in the data, affecting the quality and accuracy of the reconstructed graphics. Too many epochs might lead to overfitting where the model performs well on the training data but poorly on new, unseen data. An overfitted autoencoder might generate images that are too reliant on specific noise and details of the training data, instead of learning a more general representation of the data.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"Batch Size","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"Smaller batch sizes generally provide a more accurate gradient estimation but might lead to a less stable training process and longer training times. Smaller batches might enable the model to learn more details, potentially leading to better performance in image reconstruction tasks. Larger batch sizes can speed up training and stabilize gradient estimations but may reduce the generalization ability of the model during training. In autoencoders, too large a batch might result in reconstructed images that lack detail and appear more blurred or smooth.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"Mean Squared Error (MSE)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"a commonly used metric to measure the average squared difference between the observed actual values (targets) and the values predicted by a model. The MSE loss rate is calculated as the mean of the squares of these differences. It quantifies how well the model's predictions match the actual data, with a lower MSE indicating better performance. 5.R-Squared error(R²) also known as the coefficient of determination, is a statistical measure that indicates how well the variance in the dependent variable is explained by the independent variables in the model. It ranges from 0 to 1, with values closer to 1 indicating a better fit. R² loss rate is often used to describe the proportion of the variance that is not explained by the model.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"2.Code explanation","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"First Formula: Includes the effects of both sight and hearing","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"f = @formula 0 ~ 0 + sight + hearing 2.Second Formula: Includes only the effect of hearing fhearing = @formula 0 ~ 0 + hearing 3.Third Formula: Includes only the effect of sight fsight = @formula 0 ~ 0 + sight","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/gettingstarted/","page":"Getting Started","title":"Getting Started","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/test/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"EditURL = \"../../../literate/tutorials/test.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/test/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/test/","page":"-","title":"-","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"EditURL = \"../../../literate/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes.jl\"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/#Autoencoder","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/#Team:-Shaolong,-Ramnath-Rao-Bekal,-Rahul-Bhaskaram","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Team: Shaolong, Ramnath Rao Bekal, Rahul Bhaskaram","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/#Date:-31/8/2024","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Date: 31/8/2024","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/#1.-Definition","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"1. Definition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"1.1 Learning Rate","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Too high a learning rate might cause the model to oscillate or even diverge during training, leading to poor convergence. This could result in poor quality of the graphics generated by the autoencoder, with significant loss of detail.\nToo low a learning rate might lead to excessively slow training and the model might get stuck in local minima. This could cause the autoencoder to generate overly smooth images that miss some important features.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"1.2 Epoch Number","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Too few epochs might prevent the model from adequately learning the features in the data, affecting the quality and accuracy of the reconstructed graphics.\nToo many epochs might lead to overfitting where the model performs well on the training data but poorly on new, unseen data. An overfitted autoencoder might generate images that are too reliant on specific noise and details of the training data, instead of learning a more general representation of the data.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"1.3 Batch Size","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Smaller batch sizes generally provide a more accurate gradient estimation but might lead to a less stable training process and longer training times. Smaller batches might enable the model to learn more details, potentially leading to better performance in image reconstruction tasks.\nLarger batch sizes can speed up training and stabilize gradient estimations but may reduce the generalization ability of the model during training. In autoencoders, too large a batch might result in reconstructed images that lack detail and appear more blurred or smooth.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"1.4 Mean Squared Error (MSE)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"MSE is a commonly used metric to measure the average squared difference between the observed actual values (targets) and the values predicted by a model. The MSE loss rate is calculated as the mean of the squares of these differences. It quantifies how well the model's predictions match the actual data, with a lower MSE indicating better performance.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"1.5 R-Squared Error (R²)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"R², also known as the coefficient of determination, is a statistical measure that indicates how well the variance in the dependent variable is explained by the independent variables in the model. It ranges from 0 to 1, with values closer to 1 indicating a better fit. R² loss rate is often used to describe the proportion of the variance that is not explained by the model.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/#2.-Code-Explanation","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"2. Code Explanation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"1. First Formula: Includes the effects of both sight and hearing","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"f = @formula 0 ~ 0 + sight + hearing","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"2. Second Formula: Includes only the effect of hearing","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"f_hearing = @formula 0 ~ 0 + hearing","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"3. Third Formula: Includes only the effect of sight","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"f_sight = @formula 0 ~ 0 + sight","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"╔═╡ 549d0f75-be94-4460-9085-022f35613b29\nf = @formula 0 ~ 0 + sight + hearing\n\n╔═╡ 9ce43061-34bb-4905-b7e2-8fc5f96222cb\nf_hearing = @formula 0 ~ 0 + hearing\n\n╔═╡ e28911d6-3313-4504-90af-0cccae9d0dd8\nf_sight = @formula 0 ~ 0 + sight","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"To test and train the Deep Recurrent Encoder model, the following parameters are required:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Parameter 1: Random number generator\nParameter 2: Number of epochs\nParameter 3: Sight effect, with values of 0 or 10\nParameter 4: Time samples","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"The simulate_data function is used to create both the test and training datasets.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"data_0 and data_10 are the training datasets.\ndata_test_0 and data_test_10 are the testing datasets.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Running the simulate_data function to create the datasets:","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"data, evts = testdata.simulate_data(rng, 100, 1; sfreq=100)\n\n╔═╡ 2d073e94-e75f-4c46-950d-7fa9f4db244a\ndata_0, evts_0 = testdata.simulate_data(rng, 100, 0; sfreq=100)\n\n╔═╡ a3dd7def-6c8c-47dc-8280-933e607e424d\ndata_test_0, evts_test_0 = testdata.simulate_data(rng, 100, 0; sfreq=100)\n\n╔═╡ 374e0d33-0ad9-46ab-beb9-51b7e069ff89\ndata_10, evts_10 = testdata.simulate_data(rng, 100, 10; sfreq=100)\n\n╔═╡ 81a879b6-1077-4044-8195-bcc0d6ce1341\ndata_test_10, evts_test_10 = testdata.simulate_data(rng, 100, 10; sfreq=100)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"The R-squared error ranges from 0 to 1 and measures how closely the predicted values match the actual values. A value closer to 1 indicates that the model's predictions are a good fit with the actual data, while a value closer to 0 suggests a poor fit. In our case, the R-squared value is close to 0 due to the influence of pink noise.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"For the Mean Squared Error (MSE), the ideal value should be close to 0, indicating that the predicted and actual models are a perfect match.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Additionally, we determined the best fit for the model using a batch size of 256 and 50 hidden channels.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"To test and train the model","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"lossepochdata_hearing_0 = []\nlossepochrsquareddata_hearing_0 = []\nloss_test_rsquared_hearing_0 = []\ny_pred_hearing_0 = zeros(Float64, 44, 227, 10)\n\n# Training the model with 0 effect on sight\n# dre,ps, st = fit(DRE, Float32.(data)) # |> CuArray)\ndre, ps, st, lossepochdatahearing_0, lossepochrsquareddatahearing_0 = fit(DRE, Float32.(data_0[:,1:end÷2*2,:]) |> x->use_gpu ? CuArray(x) : x,\n    f_hearing, evts_0; n_epochs=100, mask_percentage=0.1, lr=0.1, batch_size=256, hidden_chs=50) # |> CuArray)\n\n# Testing the model with 0 effect on sight\nl, y_pred_hearing_0[:,:,:] = DeepRecurrentEncoder.test(dre, (Float32.(data_test_0[:,1:end÷2*2,:]) |> x->use_gpu ? CuArray(x) : x),\n    f_hearing, evts_test_0, ps, st; subset_index=1:10, mask_percentage=0.1, loss_function=mse)\n\npush!(lossepochdata_hearing_0, lossepochdatahearing_0)\npush!(lossepochrsquareddata_hearing_0, lossepochrsquareddatahearing_0)\npush!(loss_test_rsquared_hearing_0, l)","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/#3.-Graphs-and-Results-Explanation","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"3. Graphs and Results Explanation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Output of Predicted model","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Output of Actual model","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"The red shape corresponds to a sight effect of 0, while the blue shape corresponds to a sight effect of 10. As we can clearly observe, the blue shape is fuller and resembles a butterfly more due to the larger sight effect.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"The hearing + sight curve outperforms the hearing-only curve in terms of MSE loss, as the hearing + sight curve is closer to 0.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"As we can see, the hearing + sight*0 curve is similar to the hearing-only curve. The small differences are due to the randomly generated dataset.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Test curve R-square error curves for different hidden channels","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Predict hearing with the effect value of 10","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Training curve MSE loss improves with more epochs or more hidden layers, as it gets closer to 0.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"Training curve R-squared loss improves with more hidden channels or more epochs. The R-squared value hasn't reached 1 due to the presence of pink noise.","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"(Image: )","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"generated/tutorials/Autoencoder_EEG_Meeting_Minutes/","page":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","title":"Autoencoder EEG Meeting Minutes","text":"This page was generated using Literate.jl.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = DeepRecurrentEncoder","category":"page"},{"location":"#DeepRecurrentEncoder","page":"Home","title":"DeepRecurrentEncoder","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for DeepRecurrentEncoder.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Modules = [DeepRecurrentEncoder]","category":"page"},{"location":"#DeepRecurrentEncoder.DRE-Tuple{Int64, Int64, Int64}","page":"Home","title":"DeepRecurrentEncoder.DRE","text":"hidden_chs corresponds to the number of filters in the conv layer & the number of hidden units in the LSTM\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#DeepRecurrentEncoder.add_mask!-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{T, 3}, AbstractArray{T, 3}, Any}} where T","page":"Home","title":"DeepRecurrentEncoder.add_mask!","text":"returns new array containing eeg with mask or writes the same contents into masked if provided\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#DeepRecurrentEncoder.add_mask-Tuple{AbstractArray, Any}","page":"Home","title":"DeepRecurrentEncoder.add_mask","text":"returns new array containing eeg with mask or writes the same contents into masked if provided\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#DeepRecurrentEncoder.add_stimuli-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{T, 3}, AbstractMatrix{T}}} where T","page":"Home","title":"DeepRecurrentEncoder.add_stimuli","text":"eeg is a 3d array of shape (channel, time, epoch)\n\ndesignmatrix is a Matrix with a row discribing the stimuli for each epoch\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#DeepRecurrentEncoder.prepare_data-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Home","title":"DeepRecurrentEncoder.prepare_data","text":"Todo: Can be greatly improved by generating the stimulus matrix once and then masking + add_stimuli :shrug:\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
